tput showing an empty string, I suspect the real issue is that the embedding model is scoring the first line poorly on its own because \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" reads as incomplete without the continuation, which might be causing it to fail the relevance threshold before any of the garbled text logic even applies. So the deduplication logic is removing the longer multi-line candidate because it contains the shorter single-line version, leaving just \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" without the \"& Coriander\" part. The test output showing `Got: ''` is confusing though—I need to figure out whether that's actually what the function returned or if the test runner is just reporting it differently than what's in the results file. might just indicate the returned value.\n\nOK let me step back. I think there are a few possible explanations for `Got: ''`:\n\n1. The algorithm filtered out ALL candidates, returning undefined (shown as '')\n2. The embedding scores were all below threshold\n3. Some hard filter blocked all candidates\n\nFor the Baked Eggs case, I think the most likely issue is:\n\n- The title is split across 2 lines, with the second line starting with \"&\"\n- The 2-line join \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" is a valid candidate\n- BUT the single-line candidate \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" causes the 2-line join to be deduplicated away (since the single line is a substring of the join and shorter)\n- The single line \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" remains as the main candidate\n- If \"& Coriander\" also passes and the dedup logic leaves it, then both would be output as \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce + & Coriander\"\n\nActually, I'm wondering if the test is marking any result that doesn't exactly match the expected string as a failure, so `Got: ''` might literally mean the algorithm returned an empty string or the result didn't match. Let me reconsider the t