nd combined with the deduplication problem, the algorithm fails to surface the correct result.\n\nNow I'm synthesizing the failures across all three cases. For the first one with the baked eggs recipe, the title spans two lines which creates the core challenge.\n\nThe algorithm does build the 2-line join candidate, but then the deduplication logic kicks in—since the first line is a substring of the full join, the shorter version wins and filters out the complete candidate. This leaves just the first line as the best match, which is incomplete. The second line fragment might also be selected if it passes the threshold, but either way the algorithm fails to return the full title or returns an empty string due to how these fragmented pieces interact with the scoring logic. saying that it literally got an empty string. Could there be an issue where both title fragments cancel each other out in scoring somehow?\n\nI think I'm overthinking this without being able to run the code. Let me just write a coherent analysis based on what I can see:\n\n**Root cause for Baked Eggs**:\nThe title \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" is split across two lines in the OCR output. While `buildCandidates` does generate the 2-line join as a candidate, the dedup \"shorter wins\" filter removes the join because \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" (line 1 alone) is both a substring of the join AND shorter. This leaves only the incomplete first-line fragment plus possibly \"& Coriander\" as a confusing standalone. Since neither fragment alone represents the full title, the algorithm fails to return the correct answer. The `Got: ''` result suggests the remaining candidates scored below threshold or the algorithm returned undefined.\n\n**Failure 2 - FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS** (Got: 'FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS'):\nThe file contains two separate recipe titles: \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" (line 16) and \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" (line 29)