the second structural heading.\n\nI'm testing whether \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" can be followed by a continuation marker, but no candidates start with the expected pattern, so this becomes the first structural heading. Now I'm moving on to evaluate \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" as another structural heading.\n\nSince only the first structural heading gets the bonus, this one scores without that advantage. The continuation logic only applies to the first structural heading, so I'm comparing three candidates: the OCR garbage from the previous recipe with its structural bonus, the partial title without any bonus, and the full title with the variation.\n\nThe deduplication step removes the complete title because it contains the partial one as a substring, keeping only the shorter version. Then the OCR fragment with its structural bonus likely outscores the partial title, which has no bonus at all. I'm realizing the deduplication removes the longer variation, leaving just \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" as the shorter substring. When the multi-title guard triggers with multiple ALL_CAPS candidates, joining them with \"+\" would produce something like \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1) + SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\", which doesn't match the expected output at all. I'm realizing the dedup logic is checking if the full candidate text with \"(VARIATION 1)\" is contained as a substring in other entries, but since \"saffron wheat buns with quark\" doesn't include that exact phrase, it wouldn't be filtered out by that particular check.\n\nThe fact that only \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" appears in the actual output suggests something else is happening—maybe the scoring or filtering logic is prioritizing that result over the other, or there's a different dedup mechanism at play that I'm not accounting for. The \"Saffron Wheat Buns with Quark\" entry falls below the threshold because it lacks any positional or structural bonuses and appears late in the document.